<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Muhlenbergia</i> <i>rigens</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the herbaceous layer with <i>Aira</i> <i>caryophyllea</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>dracunculus</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>diandrus</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>hordeaceus</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>rubens</i>, <i>Carex</i> spp., <i>Centaurium</i> <i>muehlenbergii</i>, <i>Galium</i> <i>parisiense</i>, <i>Hypericum</i> <i>perforatum</i>, <i>Hypochaeris</i> <i>glabra</i>, <i>Juncus</i> spp., <i>Leymus</i> <i>triticoides</i>, <i>Logfia</i> <i>gallica</i>, <i>Lolium</i> <i>perenne</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>purshianus</i>, <i>Petrorhagia</i> <i>dubia</i>, <i>Solidago</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Trifolium</i> <i>dubium</i> and <i>Trifolium</i> <i>hirtum</i>. Emergent shrubs may be present at low cover, including <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Rubus</i> <i>armeniacus</i>, <i>Senecio</i> <i>flaccidus</i> or <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 2 m; cover is intermittent to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Muhlenbergia rigens</i> > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
		<li><i>Muhlenbergia rigens</i> > 5% absolute or > 30% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
		
		<li><i>Muhlenbergia rigens</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous canopy (Klein and Evens 2005, Nature- Serve 2007a).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Benches, lower slopes, river and stream terraces, seeps, swales, and moist slopes and moist meadow margins. Soils are well drained sands to sandy loams; they may be temporarily flooded or saturated. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Muhlenbergia rigens</i> as a FACW plant. </div>
</div>

        
