    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aj). Stands line intermittent streams in the upper San Antonio River drainage and in moist meadows between rock outcrops near “The Indians.”</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ac, Ae-f, Ah, Aj). Stands occur on sandy alluvium adjacent to streams and swales in Pinnacles National Monument (Nature- Serve 2007b) and in Wagon Caves cRNA (Keeler-Wolf 1989b, see Cheng 2004) in the Santa Lucia Mountains. They are adjacent to stands of other grassland and <i>Quercus agrifolia</i> and <i>Quercus lobata</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Al). Small stands in drainages in the Granite Mountains and perhaps other mountains of the eastern sections associate with stands of the <i>Baccharis sergiloides</i> and <i>Pinus monophylla</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eg, Ep, Er-s). Stands in Yosemite National Park at lower montane elevations are surrounded by stands of the <i>Pinus ponderosa- Calocedrus decurrens</i> and <i>Quercus kelloggii</i> alliances (Anderson 1996).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands throughout the northern two subsections (Klein et al. 2007) are mostly small (< 0.5 ha) and adjacent to streams and rivers, although some are on terraces and moist slopes associated with stands of <i>Quercus douglasii, Quercus lobata,</i> and <i>Quercus wislizeni</i> alliances. Unsampled stands exist in the southern subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf, Bj-l, Bn-o). Stands occur in low to mid elevation settings in western Riverside (Klein and Evens 2005) and San Diego Cos. (Fryer 2007, Moran 2004a, b, Sproul 2001). Some of the largest occur in Cuymaca Rancho State Park, many of which burned in 2003 (Fryer 2007). Stands typically are adjacent to other grassland alliances and stands of <i>Adenostoma sparsifolium, Ceanothus greggii, Quercus cornelius-mulleri,</i> and <i>Quercus wislizeni</i> chaparral, or <i>Pinus jeffreyi</i> and <i>Quercus kelloggii</i> woodlands.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Muhlenbergia rigens </i>has been important to at least 20 California tribes (Anderson 1996). It is one of the mainstays of Native American basketry, and substantial literature exists on traditional tribal usage and special tending of this species. Native Americans gathered culms in late spring to early fall and used thousands of f lower stalks in individual baskets. They tended dense patches of the grass with fall burning of stands every 2-5 years (Anderson 1996, 2003). However, Martin (1981) recommended spring prescribed burning to increase plant productivity. 

California tribes and other land managers are concerned about the current management of <i>M. rigens </i>stands; they deteriorate and are overtaken by woody plants, especially the highly invasive <i>Rubus armeniacus, </i>when they are not managed (Anderson 1996, 2005). Pinnacles National Monument personnel initiated a pilot program to encourage traditional Native American management and harvest (C. Striplen, pers. comm. 2007) that includes monitoring stand extent and condition. 

<i>Muhlenbergia rigens </i>is a handsome, large grass that has ornamental value. It is planted in both public and private water-conserving gardens. However, we know little about the genetic and evolutionary consequences of such actions upon natural stands. </div>
</div>

    

    

